  "prompt": "Why do converts to Islam say that they have reverted to Islam?",
  "response": "When individuals convert to Islam, they often say that they have \"reverted\" to Islam rather than \"converted.\" This terminology is rooted in the Islamic belief that every person is born in a state of natural submission to Allah, which is referred to as being born in a state of \"fitrah.\" The concept of fitrah implies that Islam is the natural and true state for humanity, and thus accepting Islam is seen as returning to one's original, natural state.\n\nThe term \"revert\" signifies that the individual is returning to this inherent state of belief and connection with Allah that they were born with, rather than adopting a completely new belief system. It's a way of expressing that Islam is believed to be the true and innate faith for all human beings.",
